<LENGTH>
<P>
690 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
ALLAN MALAMUD: NOTES ON A SCORECARD 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By ALLAN MALAMUD 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Another record appears to be in jeopardy tonight at the Sports Arena when the 
Clippers entertain Shaquille O'Neal and the Orlando Magic. . . .  
</P>
<P>
 After all, O'Neal's franchise single-game scoring record is only 53 points. . 
. . 
</P>
<P>
 Clipper General Manager Elgin Baylor was asked how opponents might be able to 
keep O'Neal in check. . . .  
</P>
<P>
 "Legally?" Baylor said. "Maybe triple-team him with big bodies. . . ." 
</P>
<P>
 O'Neal has succeeded Michael Jordan as the biggest drawing card in the NBA, 
but, surprise, plenty of good seats are available for his only Sports Arena 
appearance of the season. . . . 
</P>
<P>
 He won't return to L.A. until April 2 against the Lakers at the Forum. . . .  
</P>
<P>
 The Chicago Bulls scored 63 points against the Cleveland Cavaliers on Monday 
night. . . .  
</P>
<P>
 On March 28, 1990, Michael Jordan scored 69 against the Cavaliers. . . .  
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 Emmitt Smith's injury isn't the Dallas Cowboys' only worry. . . .  
</P>
<P>
 Troy Aikman still hasn't returned to peak form after his concussion and didn't 
complete a pass to Alvin Harper Monday night in New Orleans. . . .  
</P>
<P>
 Larry Allen, the 330-pound Dallas tackle who became an instant hero of Dan 
Dierdorf and other large people when he ran down linebacker Darion Conner after 
Conner had made an interception, played as a freshman at Compton's Centennial 
High. . . . 
</P>
<P>
 But Allen attended three schools the next three years, finished at Vintage 
High in Napa, Calif., and became the first player drafted by the NFL from 
Sonoma State, a Division II school that doesn't offer athletic scholarships. . 
. .  
</P>
<P>
 In the spring of 1987, the Tampa Bay Buccaneers traded Steve Young to the San 
Francisco 49ers for second- and fourth-round draft choices and cash. . . .  
</P>
<P>
 The Buccaneers took Miami linebacker Winston Moss, now with the Raiders, with 
the second-round pick and Arizona State wide receiver Bruce Hill with the 
fourth-round pick. . . . USC Coach John Robinson is delighted that the Trojans 
will be playing a 12th game this season. . . .  
</P>
<P>
 "We're a young team and basically we're getting an extra spring practice," he 
said about the drills that began last week for the Cotton Bowl game against 
Texas Tech on Jan. 2."We also have a new defensive line coach (Rod Marinelli) 
who's able to see what we have." . . . 
</P>
<P>
 Delon Washington, the freshman tailback who hasn't played since the Penn State 
game because of eligibility questions, has been impressive in practice and, 
according to Robinson, will get more than 10 carries against the Red Raiders. . 
. .  
</P>
<P>
 "Everything about the Cotton Bowl is very positive," Robinson said. "We'll be 
staying at a fabulous hotel and practicing at Texas Stadium next week. These 
people do it big time. About the only negative could be the weather." . . .  
</P>
<P>
 Robinson remembers his first Ram team playing the Cowboys in Irving, Tex., in 
a wild-card playoff game on Dec. 26, 1983, when the temperature was "about 15 
degrees." However, they still were able to win, 24-17. . . .  
</P>
<P>
 Thumbs up to Keyshawn Johnson, the Trojan wide receiver who spoke to young 
football players ranging from high school to Pop Warner League age Saturday at 
Jefferson High. A microphone wasn't available and he put so much into his 
inspirational talk that he lost his voice and later was speechless for one of 
the rare times in his life. . . .  
</P>
<P>
 Former USC Coach Larry Smith believes the change from artificial turf to grass 
at Missouri next season will help recruiting. . . .  
</P>
<P>
 Ivan Lendl, who retired Tuesday, never sold tickets or won a Wimbledon singles 
championship, but should be remembered for his serve, forehand and durability 
and his success in the U.S. Open. . . . 
</P>
<P>
 North Carolina is ranked first in the nation in men's basketball and fourth in 
women's. No school has scored a double in the NCAA Division I tournaments. . . 
.  
</P>
<P>
 Are you ready for pro beach soccer? Teams from the United States, Brazil, 
Italy, Argentina, Uruguay, Chile and Mexico will compete in the world 
championships in Rio de Janeiro in January, and an international tour is 
planned for next spring and summer. . . .  
</P>
<P>
 Texas Tech Coach Spike Dykes on the Nebraska Cornhuskers' size: "They're as 
big as Russia." 
</P>
