<SECTION>
<P>
Metro; Part B; Page 2 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
343 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
WEST VENTURA COUNTY FOCUS: OXNARD; PUPILS CREATE CHRISTMAS ORNAMENTS FOR 
CONVALESCENTS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By CHRISTINA LIMA 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Nine-year-old Vanessa Chester was so excited that she woke up at 6 a.m. 
Tuesday and couldn't go back to sleep. 
</P>
<P>
 "It's so much fun to give gifts that I just couldn't wait to come to school 
today," said Vanessa, a fourth-grader at Oxnard's Bernice Curren School. 
</P>
<P>
 Vanessa was one of 35 students who on Tuesday played Santa as they delivered 
ornaments and cards they had made to patients at the Glenwood Convalescent 
Hospital in Oxnard. 
</P>
<P>
 The students, who spent two weeks making the gifts, walked from their 
classroom to the hospital, where they sang Christmas carols, recited poems and 
handed out colorful Christmas cards and ornaments to about 50 patients. 
</P>
<P>
 "This is the best gift the patients can get for Christmas," said Anna 
Martinez, the hospital's activity director. "It gives them a chance to remember 
their own childhood." 
</P>
<P>
 Teacher Pat Barba said the class came up with the idea for the gifts after 
hearing about a group of youngsters cleaning up a beach; they decided that they 
too wanted to do something for the community. 
</P>
<P>
 Barba, who knew how to make ornaments, decided to make that the class project. 
</P>
<P>
 Within weeks, the classroom was cluttered with thread, needles, lace, fabric, 
pictures, glitter and strings, and students were told to be as creative as 
possible in making their ornaments. 
</P>
<P>
 The result included miniature Christmas trees, snowmen, reindeer, big and tiny 
Santas, and Christmas cards shaped like stars, cars and sleighs. 
</P>
<P>
 Lorraine Calzada got so involved in the project that she made more than 10 
cards and 10 ornaments. 
</P>
<P>
 "I like sewing and I've been excited about making the ornaments for older 
people," said Lorraine, who considers herself a sewing expert. "I made a 
blanket, two hats, and now I'm making two dolls to give my little sister for 
Christmas." 
</P>
<P>
 But not everyone was delighted with the idea of sewing. For 9-year-old Bradley 
Boer, the task was hard and tedious.  
</P>
<P>
 "I never sewed before and I don't want to do it again. I kept poking my 
finger," Bradley said. "But it was okay to make the cards." CHRISTINA LIMA 
</P>
</TEXT>
