<HEADLINE>
<P>
WEST VENTURA COUNTY FOCUS: OXNARD; POLICE IMPOSTORS RAID, RANSACK HOUSE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By IRA E. STOLL 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Five or six men pretending to be police officers stormed an Oxnard house 
Tuesday morning, assaulted the residents and ransacked the house, Oxnard police 
said. 
</P>
<P>
 Jose Javier Zendejas, 28, told authorities that the men pounded on the front 
door about 10 a.m., entered his house pointing guns and said: "This is the 
police! This is the police!" 
</P>
<P>
 Zendejas said the intruders hit him with a lead pipe and bound his hands with 
a string of Christmas tree lights before ransacking his Nottingham Drive house, 
apparently looking for drugs and money, police said. 
</P>
<P>
 Another occupant of the house, Jose Ramirez, said he was getting out of the 
shower when a man entered the bathroom, pointed a gun at him and said: "This is 
the police. Get down on the ground." 
</P>
<P>
 Ramirez told authorities that one of intruders carried a police radio. 
</P>
<P>
 Investigators said the impostors left in a red, full-size pickup truck and a 
small black pickup. 
</P>
<P>
 Police said they did not know if the assailants stole anything. 
</P>
<P>
 The investigation was disrupted when another man arrived at the house and told 
Ramirez and Zendejas to stop cooperating with police, authorities said. 
</P>
<P>
 Police said that despite the victims' subsequent lack of cooperation, they 
would continue to investigate the incident, which they called "very 
suspicious." IRA E. STOLL 
</P>
</TEXT>
