<HEADLINE>
<P>
NATION IN BRIEF; WASHINGTON, D.C.; GROUP CALLS ON FDA TO BAN SPINAL SCREWS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Staff and Wire Reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 A citizens health group petitioned the Food and Drug Administration to ban 
most uses of bone screws in the spine until they can be shown to be safe and 
effective. Public Citizen Health Research Group said the expensive and often 
dangerous screws are implanted in the spines of up to 70,000 people a year as a 
treatment for back pain. The group's report on the orthopedic screws said that 
there was a 33% complication rate and that patients were twice more likely to 
need additional spinal operations than patients getting spinal fusion without 
screws. 
</P>
</TEXT>
