<HEADLINE>
<P>
AND THEY DON'T HAVE ELVES TO HELP 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Just the facts: 
</P>
<P>
 * For 1994, 3.2 billion Christmas stamps were printed.  
</P>
<P>
 * Contemporary Christmas stamps outnumber traditional Christmas stamps, 1.9 
billion to 1.3 billion. 
</P>
<P>
 * Because Christmas is on a Sunday, the two "busiest mail days" were Dec. 12 
and Dec. 19 when about 500 million cards and letters were canceled. 
</P>
<P>
 * On Dec. 12, Southern California post offices canceled about 18.3 million 
pieces of mail. This is 70%-80% above a "normal" Monday. 
</P>
<P>
 * The largest volume of mail on Dec. 12 was canceled at the facilities in San 
Diego and Santa Ana -- 2.8 million. In contrast, Pasadena canceled 800,000. 
</P>
<P>
 * During the 1994 holiday season, 3.7 billion letters and cards are expected 
to be processed; and 30 million parcels.  
</P>
<P>
 Source: Terri Bouffion, communications specialist, U.S. Postal Service. 
</P>
</TEXT>
