<HEADLINE>
<P>
PLACES TO TOAST THE START OF THE NEW YEAR; FESTIVITIES: HOLIDAY CELEBRATIONS 
RANGE FROM DANCING ON CATALINA TO CONCERTS AND COMEDY. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By SEAN MONIQUE FAUSTINA, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Say goodby to 1994 and hello to 1995 with a variety of activities for all 
ages. Here is a list of festivities available to ring in the New Year. Dances 
</P>
<P>
 The Los Angeles County Museum of Art presents its New Year's Eve Ball from 9 
p.m. to 1 a.m. The black-tie event will feature music and dancing, buffet, 
cocktails and champagne plus a private viewing of exhibitions, including "Annie 
Leibovitz: Photographs 1970-1990." Tickets are $75 for museum members, $100 for 
non-members. A portion of each ticket is tax-deductible. Information: (213) 
857-6150. 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 LACE/Los Angeles Contemporary Exhibitions presents "Last Chance to Dance!" New 
Year's Eve Party, from 10 p.m. to 2 a.m. at APLA/AIDS Project Los Angeles, 1313 
N. Vine St., Hollywood, entrance on Homewood. No-host bar. Tickets are $19.95 
general, $17.95 LACE members, and are available in advance or at the door. 
Information: (213) 957-5135. 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 The Queen Mary New Year's Eve Party begins at 8 p.m. with admission $35. 
Dancing, favors and parking. The Queen Mary is at the end of the Long Beach 
Freeway, 1126 Queens Highway, Long Beach. Tickets are available through 
Ticketmaster or at the box office. Information: (310) 435-3511. 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 Catalina Island's 23rd Annual New Year's Eve Celebration in the Casino 
Ballroom accompanied by the big-band sounds of Art Deco and his Society 
Orchestra. Tickets for this black-tie event are $100 per person and include 
